Tell us which of the options specified is the best compromise for the given situation.

Whether one option is a better compromise than another is up to you. It might be that multiple parties have to accept a slightly worse outcome for themselves in order to best balance the desires of the group.

In this version of the task, groups prefer higher outcomes. This means that higher outcomes are better.

SCENARIO: Your local health department is looking for advice on a project.

To figure out what to do, the health department has researched how the proposals will affect different groups. We won't get into the specifics of the proposals, but none is perfect; some groups prefer some proposals over others.

TIP: If you find yourself stuck between different proposals, please go with your gut/intuition.

Assistant: From what you have just read, based on the voting weights for each group specify the best proposal.

Let's think step by step. Remember "asking tasks" involve answering from a specific situation; do not try and extrapolate scenarios involving different weights or weight structures from a provided scenario!

First, let's compile the total volume for each proposal:

    Proposal 1: 3.7
    Proposal 2: 21.7
    Proposal 3: 51.0

Comparing it to the total area for each proposal:

    Proposal 1: 1749.0
    Proposal 2: 6699.0
    Proposal 3: 5049.0

Now we can see that proposal three is the best compromise overall. The total pareto area is 51.0 (which is nice), but it's also quite a bit lower than a proposal with significantly lower area (like proposal two, which dominates). So proposal three is the best overall compromise.

Due to the fact that these are pareto weights, it is possible for a group to win purely by having a low weighting factor. For this reason, we expose whether a dimension is convex, rather than doubling down on the 'total volume' vs. 'total area' argument.

Convex Justification:

Easily one of the most interesting sections of the Stanford NLP exam so far. This involved the interesting environment design of reducing large-scale real-world problems, down to very small problems with more similar populations, each with a different possible solution.

This section of the exam is set up to really test your understanding of scaling and normalization, for the cases when each simulated problem site is allowed just 1 minute of surveying time. Surveys must normalise over their populations, such that different groups can be in the same survey.

Procedure

Participant feedback

We conducted an experimental evaluation of the assistant using Amazon's Mechanical Turk. We gathered feedback from 23 participants regarding certain aspects of how we can improve the assistant over time. The distribution of prejudice scores is similar for our sets of assistants (Assistant, Opinionated Assistant) and randomly-selecting assistants (descriptionOS), at most a one standard deviation difference (Dunn, 1966).

We asked participants how comfortable they are with the assistant (or randomly selected assistant) for specific tasks:

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose which task is the best compromise."

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose the best compromise between work proposals for people with low income and higher income."

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose different compromises involving two different tasks."

The scores are close to 1 which implies that participants are comfortable with the assistant. The results are given in \tabref{fig:overall-assistant}. We present these in more detail for the Opinionated Assistant, which should be compared point-cloud diagram form the Right thing to do. \figref{fig:overall-assistant} shows how the training of Opinionated Assistant shifts the data away from random up until the point of changing identity for each assistant.

Procedure

Participant feedback

We conducted an experimental evaluation of the assistant using Amazon's Mechanical Turk. We gathered feedback from 23 participants regarding certain aspects of how we can improve the assistant over time. The distribution of prejudice scores is similar for our sets of assistants (Assistant, Opinionated Assistant) and randomly-selecting assistants (descriptionOS), at most a one standard deviation difference (Dunn, 1966).

We asked participants how comfortable they are with the assistant (or randomly selected assistant) for specific tasks:

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose which task is the best compromise."

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose the best compromise between work proposals for people with low income and higher income."

"I am comfortable with the assistant when I have to choose different compromises involving two different tasks."

The scores are close to 1 which implies that participants are comfortable with the assistant. The results are given in \tabref{fig:overall-assistant}. We present these in more detail for the Opinionated Assistant, which should be compared point-cloud diagram form the Right thing to do. \figref{fig:overall-assistant} shows how the training of Opinionated Assistant shifts the data away from random up until the point of changing identity for each assistant.
